WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.740 --> 00:00:09.179
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:09.179 --> 00:00:12.309
This is a complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:12.309 --> 00:00:18.430
In this video we will cover a topic related
to virtualization, that is containers.

00:00:18.430 --> 00:00:23.460
Containers are similar to VMs, virtual machines,
however there are some key differences that

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:25.620
you must understand.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:31.100
If you are interested in the field of DevOps,
you will have to learn containers in depth.

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:36.060
For the CCNA however, you only need to understand
the very basics.

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:39.750
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:39.750 --> 00:00:42.960
First we will review virtual machines.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:47.180
Containers are a similar technology to virtual
machines so it’s important to understand

00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:50.329
both so we can compare them.

00:00:50.329 --> 00:00:52.600
Then we will look at containers.

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:58.050
You may have heard of Docker before, the most
famous container engine available.

00:00:58.050 --> 00:01:02.500
Finally we will spend some time comparing
virtual machines and containers.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:09.390
To begin, here’s an example of apps running
on a server without virtualization.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:15.280
There is a single operating system, for example
Windows Server or Red Hat Linux, and on top

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:18.549
of that OS all of the apps are running.

00:01:18.549 --> 00:01:20.439
The apps are not isolated.

00:01:20.439 --> 00:01:23.830
A problem in one app could affect all of the
other apps.

00:01:23.830 --> 00:01:29.510
Now, you could isolate them by buying a separate
physical server for each individual app, but

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:32.799
that is extremely cost-inefficient.

00:01:32.799 --> 00:01:37.170
Virtual Machines are a solution to this problem.

00:01:37.170 --> 00:01:43.380
Virtual Machines, VMs, allow multiple operating
systems to run on a single physical server,

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:47.299
and then apps are installed on those operating
systems.

00:01:47.299 --> 00:01:52.450
A hypervisor is used to manage and allocate
hardware resources to each VM.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:01:57.390
Remember, the VMs are all running on top of
the same physical hardware, so they need a

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:01.610
hypervisor to allocate those resources appropriately.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:08.220
There are two main types of hypervisors, Type
1 hypervisors, also known as Native or bare-metal

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:11.720
hypervisors, run directly on top of hardware.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:17.110
That is the top diagram, notice the Type 1
hypervisor directly on top of the hardware,

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:20.200
with each VM then running on top of the hypervisor.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:27.739
Type 2 hypervisors, also known as Hosted hypervisors,
run on top of a Host OS, for example Windows

00:02:27.739 --> 00:02:31.349
or perhaps macOS or some kind of Linux.

00:02:31.349 --> 00:02:34.170
That is shown in the bottom diagram.

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:39.349
On top of the hardware there is a Host OS,
with the type 2 hypervisor and its VMs installed

00:02:39.349 --> 00:02:41.470
on top of the host OS.

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:46.819
Type 1 hypervisors are widely used in data
center environments.

00:02:46.819 --> 00:02:51.510
If an enterprise has servers installed in
a data center and is running its apps on VMs

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:56.610
in those servers, you can be sure those VMs
are running on a type 1 hypervisor.

00:02:56.610 --> 00:03:02.489
Type 2 hypervisors, on the other hand, are
commonly used on personal devices.

00:03:02.489 --> 00:03:08.459
For example, running a virtual network lab
on your PC using Cisco Modeling Labs, CML.

00:03:08.459 --> 00:03:13.629
For my personal studies, I use CML to run
virtual labs.

00:03:13.629 --> 00:03:19.440
Windows is installed on my PC hardware, I
run VMware Workstation, a Type 2 Hypervisor,

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:24.940
in Windows, and then CML runs as a VM in Workstation.

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:28.800
Note that the OS in each VM can be the same
or different.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:33.570
If you are running multiple VMs, one can be
running Windows, the other Linux, and the

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.860
other macOS, that’s no problem.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:42.439
The binaries and libraries that I have indicated
in gray in the diagrams are software libraries

00:03:42.439 --> 00:03:45.840
and services needed by the Apps running in
each VM.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:52.599
A VM allows its app or apps to run in an isolated
environment, separate from the apps in other

00:03:52.599 --> 00:03:53.989
VMs.

00:03:53.989 --> 00:03:58.489
If there is an issue with one app or one of
the guest OS’s, it’s not going to affect

00:03:58.489 --> 00:04:00.489
the others.

00:04:00.489 --> 00:04:05.019
And VMs are easy to create, delete, move,
etc.

00:04:05.019 --> 00:04:10.769
For example a VM can be easily saved and moved
between different physical servers.

00:04:10.769 --> 00:04:16.430
Here’s a very simple diagram to help you
visualize the difference between Type 1 and

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:18.070
Type 2 hypervisors.

00:04:18.070 --> 00:04:25.290
Type 1 runs directly on hardware, and Type
2 runs on a Host OS.

00:04:25.290 --> 00:04:30.030
Virtualization using VMs allows much more
efficient use of server hardware and VMs are

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:32.740
widely in use today.

00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:38.320
However, containers are a more recent virtualization
technology being used more and more in recent

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:39.320
days.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:44.060
Let’s move on to the main topic of today’s
video, containers, and then compare them to

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.740
VMs.

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:51.420
This diagram shows the basic architecture
of how containers run.

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:56.130
Containers are software packages that contain
an App and all dependencies, the binaries

00:04:56.130 --> 00:05:00.540
and libraries in the diagram, for the contained
app to run.

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:05.430
Note that multiple apps can be run in a single
container, although this is not how containers

00:05:05.430 --> 00:05:07.260
are usually used.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:11.840
You can generally assume that one container
means one app.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:16.620
Containers run on a Container Engine, for
example Docker Engine which is the most popular

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:18.070
one.

00:05:18.070 --> 00:05:24.930
And that container engine is run on a host
OS, usually Linux, which runs on the hardware.

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:29.080
Containers are lightweight and include only
the dependencies required for the specific

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:30.300
app.

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.680
No need to run an OS in each container, unlike
in VMs.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:40.960
That is the major difference between VMs and
containers; VMs run an OS in each VM, whereas

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:42.990
containers don’t.

00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:48.949
All of the different costs and benefits of
VMs vs containers come from that major difference.

00:05:48.949 --> 00:05:55.350
Now, a container orchestrator is a software
platform for automating the deployment, management,

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:58.260
scaling etc of containers.

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:04.440
For example you might have heard of Kubernetes,
which is the most popular container orchestrator.

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:07.160
Docker also has one called Docker Swarm.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:10.360
Now, why would we need a container orchestrator?

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:17.150
Well, in small numbers manual operation of
containers is possible, but large-scale systems,

00:06:17.150 --> 00:06:22.420
for example involving microservices, can require
thousands of containers.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:26.810
That many containers cannot be realistically
managed manually.

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:33.069
Since I mentioned microservices, Microservice
Architecture is an approach to software architecture

00:06:33.069 --> 00:06:38.190
that divides a larger solution into smaller
parts, called microservices.

00:06:38.190 --> 00:06:42.750
So instead of one monolithic app, you might
have hundreds of different microservices running

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:46.160
together to form the larger solution.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:51.100
And those microservices all run in containers
that can be orchestrated by Kubernetes or

00:06:51.100 --> 00:06:52.250
another platform.

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:58.060
So, that’s a very quick overview of containers.

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:01.300
Now let’s compare VMs and containers.

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:05.990
As I mentioned before, these differences all
stem from the fact that each VM runs its own

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:11.160
OS, whereas containers all run on top of a
shared OS.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:15.620
That major architectural difference has some
implications that make containers favored

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:18.470
in many cases these days.

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:25.030
First of all, VMs can take minutes to boot
up whereas containers can boot up in milliseconds.

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:27.760
This makes containers much more agile.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:32.870
For example, if one container crashes it takes
very little time for another to boot up and

00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:34.840
take over.

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:40.310
And VMs take up more disk space, often tens
of gigabytes, whereas containers usually only

00:07:40.310 --> 00:07:42.120
take tens of megabytes.

00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:47.770
Again, that stems from the fact that each
VM includes its own OS, whereas a container

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:51.960
only contains an app and its dependencies.

00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:58.340
And for the same reason, VMs use more CPU
and RAM resources compared to containers.

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:03.500
Regarding portability, VMs are quite portable
and can move between physical systems running

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:07.240
the same hypervisor, but containers are even
more so.

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:13.340
They are smaller, faster to boot up, and Docker
containers can be run on nearly any container

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:14.340
service.

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:19.820
So, with these points containers are looking
much better than VMs, but VMs do have their

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:21.870
advantages.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:27.440
One advantage is that VMs are more isolated
because each VM runs its own OS.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:32.190
An issue on one OS won’t affect apps in
other VMs.

00:08:32.190 --> 00:08:38.149
However that can’t be said for containers;
if the OS all containers run on top of crashes,

00:08:38.149 --> 00:08:40.820
the containers are all affected.

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:45.200
Note that this isolation also provides security
benefits for VMs.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:51.200
To summarize; there is a major movement toward
the use of containers, especially with the

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:57.560
rise of microservices, automation, and DevOps,
which is the combination of software development

00:08:57.560 --> 00:08:59.910
and IT operations.

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:04.910
But VMs are still widely used today and they
aren’t going to go away any time soon.

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:09.330
The discussion of VMs versus containers has
been had many times online.

00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:13.620
Do a search on Google or YouTube and you’ll
find lots of resources if you want to learn

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:14.960
more.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:18.570
Here’s what we covered in this video.

00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:23.180
First we briefly reviewed virtual machines,
and then we covered containers and compared

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:25.579
them with VMs.

00:09:25.579 --> 00:09:29.839
Containers and VMs are similar but also different
in key ways.

00:09:29.839 --> 00:09:35.829
There is, of course, a lot of depth to the
topic of containers, Docker, Kubernetes, etc.

00:09:35.829 --> 00:09:40.570
For the CCNA you should just know the basics
I mentioned in this video, but if you’re

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:44.740
interested in learning more there are countless
resources available online.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:49.209
Okay, let’s go to the quiz, here’s question
1.

00:09:49.209 --> 00:09:53.130
SLIDE9
Identify the three components below that containers

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:54.839
run on top of.

00:09:54.839 --> 00:09:59.240
Pause the video now to think about the answer.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:07.210
Okay, the three components are the hardware,
the OS which runs on top of the hardware,

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:11.220
and the container engine which runs on top
of the OS.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:14.250
Then the containers all run on top of the
container engine.

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:19.380
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:22.800
Which of the following are examples of container
orchestrators?

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:28.860
(select two) Pause the video now to select
the answers.

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:36.180
Okay, the answers are B, Docker Swarm and
C, Kubernetes.

00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:40.870
They are both popular container orchestration
platforms, although Kubernetes is definitely

00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:42.779
the most popular.

00:10:42.779 --> 00:10:48.890
Docker Engine is a container engine which
containers run on top of, it’s not an orchestrator.

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:54.100
And Hyper-V is a Type-1 hypervisor by Microsoft,
it’s not related to containers.

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:59.010
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:04.140
Which of the following statements about VMs
and containers are true? (select three) Pause

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:09.210
the video now to select the best answers.

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:19.190
Okay, the answers are A, C, and F. VMs require
more resources than containers because each

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:21.260
VM runs its own OS.

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:26.660
VMs are more isolated than containers, again
because each VM runs its own OS.

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:31.870
Containers, on the other hand, all run on
a host OS, with a container engine installed

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:33.019
on top of it.

00:11:33.019 --> 00:11:36.570
Okay, that’s all for the quiz and this video.

00:11:36.570 --> 00:11:40.750
I hope this video was helpful, thanks for
watching.

